People ask me if I ever shoot color photos.  I do. If you scroll through my feed, you’ll see plenty of color photos.  Almost all are done with my iPhone… those being the  landscapes and such.  With my portrait work for the book project, I focus on black and white.  I started shooting for the book using black and white film stocks.  But now, when shooting digital, I will many times do color edits because I love the color that was captured.  In my color work I tend to move away from reality, go more desaturated or the opposite and go very saturated.  Sometimes I like one color to dominate the frame.  Here are some of my color photos from the past few years.  What do you think? 
.
.
.

My heart is broken.  Very hard day as I had to say goodbye to my beautiful boy, Jinky.  He was 19 years old.  He lived a long and happy life.  So I take some comfort in that.  But I am empty without him and it will take time to fill this huge hole.  He was always a very loving cat.  He loved everyone he met and always wanted to be on your lap or lick your face.  To Jinky there were no strangers.  Only new friends to love on.  If you walked through the door, he wanted to know you immediately.  He was playful until the end, even when he slowed down.  He loved being in the sunshine and would move all day long, laying down in the ever shifting light.  In the summer when the patch of sunlight no longer fell on the carpet, but outside on the porch, he cried to go out to the sun and would follow that small patch of light until it faded away.  Today I lay with him in a patch of sunlight on the carpet one last time.  He felt the sun, felt my hand gently stroking his fur.  Then I said my goodbye and made sure he knew I was there as he fell asleep in the warm embrace of the sunlight he loved so much.  Farewell sweet Jinky.  I know you are in a better place, cuddling with your brother Casper again.

Jinky was preceded by his brother Casper a few years earlier.  Jinky mourned for weeks.  The two were inseparable.  They were brothers.  They were from the same litter, rescued as kittens and brought to Cat Connection in Sherman Oaks.  It was almost 20 years ago that I spotted Casper in the window one night after leaving dinner.  I named him Casper that night.  It just came to me.  He was in the store front playing with the other cats and kittens.  He was a little fur ball and played with me through the glass.  I went home thinking I would return the next day just to hold him.  I thought my busy travel schedule for work would make it hard for me to have a cat.  But I went back the next day.  When I picked Casper up, I knew I was going to take him home.  But there was this other, skinny, big eared, orange and white little kitten that would not leave me alone.  He cried and followed me around, but I was there to get only one cat.  I couldn’t possibly take two.  Then as I was doing the paperwork for Casper I heard this persistent meow over my shoulder.  It was that orange and white kitten.  He had somehow climbed up the screen door to the enclosure behind me and was spread out, hanging on the mesh meowing so loud.  The woman helping me looked up from the paperwork and said that he was Casper’s brother and they had come in together.  Ugh.  Okay, give me both of them.  So I left with my two boys.  On the way to the car I saw the name of a breakfast spot I frequented, Jinkys Cafe.  And Jinky had his name.  So I had picked Casper.  But Jinky had picked me.  I always said to him… You picked me and made my life all the better.  I will miss you always, Jinky.  But you are reunited with Casper now.  And forever at play together.
.
.

Some years back I directed a special for The Discovery Channel about Napoleon’s campaign in Russia.  The docudrama focused specifically on the disastrous retreat that took him through Vilinius, Lithuania where he lost thousands of men.  I recently saw some photos from Ridley Scott’s upcoming Napoleon film and I was reminded of the three months I spent in Vilnius directing this project.  It was an amazing experience.  We shot some in Russia, but the bulk of it in Vilnius, Lithuania.  In the streets of Old Town and countryside.  We also built wonderful sets on stages at an old Russian film studio that had been privatized.  The wardrobe department there created some incredible uniforms, bringing historical accuracy to every frame in the most minute details.  One of the big thrills of the show was re-staging Napoleon’s army entering Vilnius through the Gates of Dawn on June 28th, 1812.  To do this we closed down the city center in old town, took down modern signs, street lights.  The city and mayor aided in the weeks long preparation.  Then we closed down that area for 5 hours one Sunday morning and marched hundreds of extras and horses through the actual Gates of Dawn.  It was like stepping back in time watching that unfold as I called action.  You can see the Gates of Dawn in these photos.  I shot these myself on 35mm color film stock. I like to capture moments, faces and in this case,  the epic scale of what we were creating.  What do you think ?  Epic or what? 
.
.

From a recent shoot with my friend @sebastianaction. I’ve directed Sebastian in several projects over the years and his passion for acting, film and the arts drew us together.  Long, tough location shoots only energized his performances and bonded us in creative friendship.  Sebastian and I had been trying to do a photo shoot together for a few years and busy schedules, moves and life always got in the way.  Then life really got in the way in the form of a motorcycle accident that left Sebastian in pretty bad shape.  Many months of rehabilitation and ultimately the loss of an arm followed.  All of which has tested him and continues to test him daily.  During this recovery, I’ve tried to get him in front of my lens, but he wasn’t ready. Understandably so.  But in this past year he has returned to acting, slowly reclaiming his passions.  I was excited when he said he felt ready to step in front of my camera and trust me to capture him now, on the other side of this journey.  We’re all battered and beaten up by life, some of us in ways that test us more than others.  The artist channels it all into the art and Sebastian is doing that.  I love these photos we did with his new arm and the balloons.  There was something visually striking about the dark and light balloons in contrast to the soft whiteness of his flesh arm and the sleek dark of his mechanical arm.  And the lightness and playfulness of balloons also seemed fitting to the place in life where he is at now.  Only up.  Treasuring life and the opportunities to create.  Thank you @sebastianaction for trusting me, sharing time and creating together.

I’ve been a WGA member since 1986 and this is my 3rd strike.  I’ve never seen such an outpouring of support and enthusiasm for our cause.  This is an inflection point for our industry and our craft.  I have enjoyed the benefits and creative protections of this guild for many years.  This new generation of writers deserves the same for years to come.  Fair compensation, opportunity to jobs and a strong pension and health fund that will be there in the future.  We all need to make our voices heard.  This industry is rapidly changing.  And as writers we need to able to reap the benefits of our creative contributions.  It all begins with a script.  All of it.  Respect the written word.  And those who write. 
.
.

As I walked down to the Village Dock to capture a sunset shot, I could see a group of kids leaping off the dock with shouts of joy.  There is nothing better than jumping into Cayuga Lake after a hot, sweaty day.  Seeing their sheer joy in the moment immediately took me back to my own youth and the many summer days and nights I spent on that dock.  Swim lessons when I was just a boy, fishing and boating as a teen, my first time swimming all the way out to the raft, a late night swim with my high school crush.  So many memories flooded back of those carefree summers spent watching sunsets, spent taking carefree leaps off the dock.  Plunging into the cool waters of Cayuga Lake.  Then doing it again.  As I watched the boys line up and race ahead for another plunge, I snapped this frame.  Frozen in time, a leap of carefree youth.  A time to enjoy the endless summer.  What a time in life it was.  What a time in life it is. 
.
.
.

These are from a shoot I did earlier this summer with Canadian actor @abdallamour.  I had the good fortune to cast Abdalla in one of the leads of a Netflix series that I was directing up in Canada earlier this year.  He had to dye his hair blond for the role and shortly after we finished shooting in Canada, Abdalla was passing through Los Angeles and I asked him to do a shoot for my project while he still had his blond hair.  We kept the locations and concept simple, working with a few props and simple, natural light.  We also focused on emotions and thoughts, connecting those into the lens rather than poses or wardrobe.  Abdalla brings such genuine emotions to a role and is comfortable doing the same for a still shoot.  It was a pleasure creating with him as both actor and subject for these images. 
.

Some incredible views from my recent hike up The Narrows in Zion National Park with my dear friend, Nathan West.  Look closely in the photos, you’ll sometimes see a very tiny Nathan in the bottom of frame for scale.  This hike has long been on my list and it didn’t disappoint.  You hike most of the way through a swift moving river that can knock you off your feet at peak flow points and force you to wade through chest deep pools with your pack over your head to get further up the slot canyon.  But the views are Incredible!!! I was looking down so much to not trip over submerged rocks that I had to stop and look up at the stunning cliffs that rose on either side of me.  It was like stepping back in time or being on another planet. The further up we went, the harder the trek got, but the fewer people that followed.  Soon we had the narrow, breathtaking canyon to ourselves.  We went as far as we could until piles of giant boulders prevented us from continuing on without canyoneering gear.  So grateful to have had this time and the strength to make it through this stunning piece of landscape. 
.
.

location.city_name: Angel's Landing, Zion National Park, Utah

social_posts.post_text:
The hike to the top of Angel’s Landing has been on my bucket list since I was in college.  To finally pull it off all these years later is an incredible feeling.  The lure and reputation of this hike is unmatched.  Labeled “the most dangerous hike” in America, it lives up to its reputation.  Seventeen people have fallen to their death off the steep cliff trail.  Take this trail seriously!!! It was not easy and very sketchy in places where the path is only a few feet wide with 1600 foot drops to either side.  Nathan and I started early in the dark.  Best move.  I would not want to be passing people on those cliffs.  As we we climbed the steep trail, we encountered people coming back who had turned around due to the high wind.  We decided to keep going.  A chain attached to the cliff wall is your only safety from tumbling to your death at points.  So I only have a few photos.  Both hands were on that chain!!! We did make it to the top, greeted by an incredible sunrise cresting the Zion Canyon.  The views at the top were breathtaking.  The trip down was even more sketchy, climbing backwards at points and navigating past other people coming up.  Made it to the bottom, sore and scraped up, but alive and exhilarated.  I found this climb much scarier than the Half Dome cables, but not physically as hard.  Glad to have done it.  Probably won’t do it again. Lol
.
.

I’m shooting film again!!! I shot 35mm B&W film stock for the first time in about 10 years.  And of course you can’t beat it.  You cannot replace those rich blacks and the range it holds.  I pulled out my old canon EOS Elan body and took it along to this most recent shoot and loaded up some TMX-100.  Shot the 36 exposures across the course of the shoot while shooting digital as well.  When I scanned the negs, I barely had to edit the images, save for dust specs and a little contrast / brightness adjustment.  To try and make the digital images emulate the film took more time, but I think I got pretty close.  But this shoot totally makes me want to go back to shooting only film again.  The first four images of this series are digital.  The second four images are film.

I asked my friends Evan and Brena to help me homage one of my favorite photographers, brucedavidson.  I love his work, particularly his book, BROOKLYN GANGS, which was a collection of images of young people he shot in 1959.  The natural lighting under piers, in subways and along Coney Island was beautiful and there was a somewhat  voyaristic quality to his shots.  Not creepy, but just a beautiful window into emotionally private and vulnerable moments.  Arguments, romance, sadness, playfulness.  With Eva and Brena I tried to capture that young love and romantic exploration that so defined the Davidson photos.  Thanks to his inspiration and Evan and Brena’s chemistry, I was able to create these images that I’m quite happy with.  Can you see the difference in the digital and film images?

The RISE FESTIVAL 2023 was nothing short of magical.  Releasing the Japanese paper  lanterns into the night sky with close to 20k other people all at once is a breathtaking and beautiful sight.  There are two releases.  On one lantern you write the things you want to release from your life.  On the other lantern you write your affirmations.  Then release them at different times just after sunset over a the dry lake bed in the Nevada desert. The visual of it is stunning, but with the music and collective energy of the crowd it is quite a spiritual and emotional event.  Wonderful experience. 
.
.
